{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516695"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:45:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:45:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12691"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12691"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.2,0.58,0.05,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5157"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54638"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5157"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12691"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40159"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2078"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"},{"type":"tags","id":"2765"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8710"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8799"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16417"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54638"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-hour history of central crushing chest pain, shortness of breath, and sweating. He has a medical history of hypertension and dyslipidaemia. His regular medications are rosuvastatin and perindopril. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 96/min, blood pressure 220/130 mmHg, respiratory rate 35/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. On auscultation of the chest, heart sounds are dual without murmur and there are bibasilar crackles. Investigations reveal a troponin level of 1000 ng/mL (0-14). An ECG is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely pathophysiological cause of these ECG findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pericarditis","Coronary artery dissection","Acute plaque rupture","Pericardial haemorrhage","Coronary artery spasm"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely cause of the patient\u0027s presentation is an ST elevation myocardial infarction. This is caused by an \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute plaque rupture\u003C/strong\u003E in one of the coronary arteries, leading to thrombosis and subsequent myocardial infarction. The ECG findings of ST elevation in III and aVF with reciprocal changes in aVL are consistent with an inferior wall myocardial infarction, which is commonly caused by occlusion of the right coronary artery. There is also ST depression in leads V2-V6. The elevated troponin levels also support the diagnosis of myocardial infarction. The patient\u0027s risk factors for this include hypertension and dyslipidaemia, as well as age and male sex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPericarditis\u003C/strong\u003E is inflammation of the pericardium, the membrane surrounding the heart. ECG findings in pericarditis typically include diffuse ST elevation with PR depression, which is not seen in this patient\u0027s ECG. Troponin levels may be mildly elevated in pericarditis, but not to the extent seen in myocardial infarction. In addition, the patient\u0027s bibasilar crackles on lung auscultation suggest pulmonary oedema, which is not a typical feature of pericarditis. Furthermore, the quality of the pain is usually pleuritic in nature, relieved by leaning forward. There is usually a viral precipitant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoronary artery dissection\u003C/strong\u003E may include ST elevation or depression depending on the location and extent of the dissection. Troponin levels may be elevated if myocardial infarction occurs as a result of the dissection. However, coronary artery dissection is not likely to present with the specific ECG findings seen in this patient, which are consistent with an inferior wall myocardial infarction caused by an acute plaque rupture in a coronary artery. In addition, the patient\u0027s history of hypertension and dyslipidaemia are more commonly associated with atherosclerotic plaque rupture than coronary artery dissection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPericardial haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E can lead to cardiac tamponade and haemodynamic compromise. ECG findings in pericardial haemorrhage may include electrical alternans, which is not seen in this patient\u0027s ECG. Elevated troponin levels would not be expected in pericardial haemorrhage unless there is concomitant myocardial infarction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoronary artery spasm\u003C/strong\u003E is a transient narrowing of a coronary artery, leading to myocardial ischaemia. ECG findings in coronary artery spasm may include ST elevation, but typically not in a specific distribution such as seen in this patient\u0027s ECG. Elevated troponin levels would not be expected in coronary artery spasm unless there is concomitant myocardial infarction. Furthermore, the patient\u0027s presentation is not typical for coronary artery spasm, which is more commonly seen in younger patients without significant risk factors for coronary artery disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the patient\u0027s presentation with typical chest pain, ECG changes consistent with inferior wall myocardial infarction, and significantly elevated troponin levels strongly support the diagnosis of acute myocardial infarction due to plaque rupture. This is further supported by the patient\u0027s risk factors and age. The other options, while potential causes of chest pain and ECG changes, do not fit as well with the clinical picture presented.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute plaque rupture is the most likely pathophysiological cause for a patient presenting with signs and symptoms of myocardial infarction.","ECG findings of ST elevation in leads III and aVF with reciprocal changes in aVL are consistent with an inferior wall myocardial infarction.","Elevated troponin levels, along with typical ECG changes, support the diagnosis of myocardial infarction."],"references":["Mechanic OJ, Gavin M, Grossman SA. Acute Myocardial Infarction. 2022 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29083808.","Zimetbaum PJ, Josephson ME. Use of the electrocardiogram in acute myocardial infarction. N Engl J Med. 2003 Mar 6;348(10):933-40. doi: 10.1056/NEJMra022700. PMID: 12621138."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40159"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12691"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19792"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19792"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7d8393ad-bfdd-4ee5-8b5a-b296c9e476c4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7d8393ad-bfdd-4ee5-8b5a-b296c9e476c4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":355}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40159"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-08T19:01:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-08T19:05:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5157"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questi